DELETE A NODE IN A BINARY SEARCH TREE (BST)

You are given a Binary Search Tree (BST) and a value X. Your task is to delete the node with value X from the BST and return the root of the modified tree.

The solution involves two main steps:

Search for the node with value X.
If the node is found, delete it while maintaining the BST properties.

INPUT FORMAT:

The first line contains two integers:
N X
where
N is the number of nodes in the BST
X is the value of the node to be deleted

The next (N - 1) lines describe the tree edges.
Each line contains:
pi ci Ri

where
pi is the parent node value
ci is the child node value
Ri represents the relationship:
L means ci is the left child of pi
R means ci is the right child of pi

OUTPUT FORMAT:

Return the root of the modified BST after deleting node X.

CONSTRAINTS:

1 ≤ N ≤ 10000
1 ≤ pi, ci ≤ 100000
All node values are distinct
Ri is either L or R
1 ≤ X ≤ 100000

SAMPLE INPUT:

10 8
3 1 L
8 3 L
8 11 R
11 9 L
13 8 L
13 19 R
18 16 L
19 18 L
19 20 R

SAMPLE OUTPUT:

Successfully deleted the node!


